There are several layered issues. Here they are ordered from most to least likely as your root cause:

Problem 1 — Queued frames contain pre-trigger data (most likely root cause)
Where: background_worker.py:58-84 + mh_recruitment_curve_stage.py:398-431

The BackgroundWorker is a QRunnable in a separate thread. It calls data_received_signal.emit(df) in a tight loop. Because this signal crosses thread boundaries into the Qt main thread, it automatically becomes a queued connection — frames pile up in the main thread's event queue.

When process() is called and detects threshold → calls trigger_single() → the signal queue may already have several older frames waiting. These frames were acquired by Open Ephys before the trigger was sent. The main thread then processes them all in TRIAL_STATE_RECORD, happily accumulating pre-trigger data. By the time it reaches 150ms worth of samples, the sync line data contains no stim pulse. The onset search finds nothing → fallback is used → stim end = 0.

This is intermittent because it only happens when the main thread is slightly behind (plotting, UI updates, Python GIL).

Problem 2 — Large block sizes can fill the entire recording in one shot
Where: background_worker.py:78, mh_recruitment_curve_stage.py:440-442

The frame is emitted the moment all 3 channels arrive. Open Ephys sends blocks of typically 256 samples. Depending on sample rate:

At 2500 Hz → 256 samples = ~102 ms per block
At 10 kHz → 256 samples = ~25.6 ms per block
At 30 kHz → 256 samples = ~8.5 ms per block
The RECORD state needs bin_sample_count() + trial_recording_sample_count() = 50ms + 100ms = 150ms total samples to finalize. If you're running at a lower sample rate, a single 256-sample block could supply enough samples to finalize the recording immediately. That single post-trigger block was likely acquired before the pulse fired, so no onset is found.

Problem 3 — No trigger timestamp is recorded
Where: mh_recruitment_curve_stage.py:429-431

trigger_single() is called but the wall-clock time is never stored. The onset search at lines 614-626 is purely positional — it assumes the stim onset will appear somewhere in sync_data[bin_sample_count() : bin_sample_count()+trial_recording_sample_count()]. There is no way to verify whether the collected sync data was acquired before or after the trigger. If you recorded datetime.now() when trigger_single() was called and used timestamp_received_millis on each incoming block, you could skip blocks that arrived before that time.

Problem 4 — Fallback onset always produces stim_end = 0 (misleading display)
Where: mh_recruitment_curve_stage.py:620, lines 659-665

The fallback when no onset is found:


stim_onset_idx: int = MhRecruitmentCurveStage.bin_sample_count()  # fallback
The stim-end search then starts at sync_data[bin_sample_count()]. If no stim artifact is present, that sample is at baseline (<1.0V), so end_candidates[0] = 0, giving stim_end_time_ms = 0. The purple end line plots on top of the blue onset line. This is what you're seeing as "stim period of 0" — it specifically means onset was not found, fallback was used, not that the stim actually had zero duration.

Problem 5 — Single-sample noise spike gives near-zero stim period
Where: mh_recruitment_curve_stage.py:624-626

If any electrical transient on the ADC channel (coupling from the stimulator trigger circuit, for example) produces even one sample ≥ 3.0V in the search window, it's detected as onset. The very next sample drops back to baseline, so end_candidates[0] = 1, giving stim_end_time_ms ≈ 0.03–0.4 ms (depending on sample rate) — visually indistinguishable from 0 on the plot.

Problem 6 — Commented-out timestamp guard in frame assembly
Where: background_worker.py:67


if (df is None):# or ((df is not None) and (result.timestamp != df.timestamp)):
The original check that would start a new frame when the timestamp changes was commented out. This means if Open Ephys sends blocks from two different time windows out of order, all 3 channels of a frame are just collected in arrival order with no timestamp validation. A mismatch between the EMG block's time window and the sync block's time window would shift the stim onset relative to the EMG signal, causing the snippet to show the wrong segment.

Summary Table
#	Problem	Effect	Intermittent?
1	Qt queued signal delivers pre-trigger frames to RECORD state	Onset missing, stim_end = 0	Yes — depends on main thread load
2	Large block size fills RECORD with one pre-trigger block	Same as above	Yes — sample-rate dependent
3	No trigger timestamp tracked	Cannot distinguish pre/post-trigger frames	Always latent
4	Fallback onset renders stim_end = 0	Misleading "zero duration" display	Whenever 1–3 occur
5	Noise transient false-positive onset	Snippet anchored to noise, near-zero duration	Yes — noise dependent
6	Commented-out timestamp guard	EMG/sync misalignment in frame	Rare
The fix for the core issue (1 + 3) would be to record datetime.now() at the moment trigger_single() is called and compare against timestamp_received_millis on incoming blocks during the RECORD state, discarding any block that was received before the trigger call.

