Plain-English Walkthrough
process() — What it does
NOT_SETUP state: Picks the next stim amplitude from the randomized list, sends it to the stimulator hardware, and moves to WAIT_FOR_INITIATION.

WAIT_FOR_INITIATION state: Every incoming data frame, checks if the muscle EMG is within the initiation threshold window. Once it is:

Grabs the last 50 ms of EMG from the rolling buffer → trial_data (pre-stim portion)
Grabs the last 50 ms of ADC sync from the rolling buffer → sync_data (pre-stim portion)
Records _trigger_wall_time_ms = wall-clock time right now
Fires trigger_single() on the stimulator
RECORD state: Receives incoming frames. Discards any frame whose timestamp_emitted (set by the background thread when the frame was assembled) is earlier than _trigger_wall_time_ms. Keeps the rest, concatenating onto trial_data and sync_data until 100 ms of post-stim data has accumulated. Then moves to FINALIZE.

FINALIZE state: Saves, plots, resets.

_update_trial_plot() — What it does
After FINALIZE, trial_data and sync_data each look like:


index:  0 ............ trigger_sample .............. end
data:   [50ms pre-stim] [post-trigger frames ...]
         ↑                 ↑
     pre-stim EMG    stim pulse should be somewhere in here
Phase 1 searches sync_data for where the ADC line crossed 4.5 V (stim onset). It never looks in the pre-stim half. It starts at trigger_sample + extra_delay_samples and looks 120 ms forward.

Phase 2 cuts a ±20/+30 ms slice of EMG around wherever it decided onset was.

Phase 3 builds the x-axis so that the onset sample = t=0 ms.

Phase 4 finds the stim end on the sync line after the onset (only if onset was found).

Phase 5 optionally overlays the ADC sync line on the same plot.

The Real Problem You're Describing
Yes — the extra_delay_samples calculation is the most likely cause of misalignment on successful trials.

Here's why:


ms_delay = frame_received_timestamps_ms[0] - trigger_wall_time_ms
extra_delay_samples = min(ms_delay * sample_rate / 1000, 60ms_in_samples)
search_start = trigger_sample + extra_delay_samples
ms_delay measures: how long after the trigger did the first post-trigger frame finish assembling? That's a Qt/ZMQ frame delivery latency, not a hardware stim arrival latency. These are different:

The Model 4100 fires its pulse with a fixed hardware delay after trigger_single() — likely < 1 ms
The first post-trigger frame may not finish assembling until 5–30 ms later
So search_start skips past where the pulse actually landed in the data. On bad trials, the search window starts after the pulse and never finds it. On "successful" trials with this issue, it found a later noise crossing and zero'd to the wrong place.

Where to Breakpoint
Breakpoint 1 — in RECORD state, inside if frame_is_post_trigger:

Right after self._frame_received_timestamps_ms.append(...). Inspect:

Variable	What to check
data_frame.timestamp_emitted	When did this frame arrive?
self._trigger_wall_time_ms	When was the trigger sent?
data_frame.timestamp_emitted - self._trigger_wall_time_ms	Frame delay in ms — is this 5ms? 30ms?
len(self._current_trial.sync_data)	Growing correctly each frame?
self._current_trial.sync_data.max()	Does the pulse appear at all yet?
Breakpoint 2 — in _update_trial_plot(), just before the print(f"[DEBUG] onset search ...") line

This is the single most important breakpoint. Inspect:

Variable	What to check
trigger_sample	Expected: ~1500 at 30 kHz
extra_delay_samples	If > 300 samples (10ms), the search may skip past the pulse
search_start / search_end	Is the window reasonable?
self._current_trial.sync_data[trigger_sample:].max()	Peak voltage in the entire post-trigger region — is the pulse even there?
self._current_trial.sync_data[search_start:search_end].max()	Peak voltage within the search window — if lower than 4.5 V, the window is wrong
onset_was_detected	Did it find anything?
stim_onset_idx	Where t=0 will be placed
Breakpoint 3 — in _update_trial_plot(), after Phase 2 (idx_pre, idx_post calculated)

Inspect:

Variable	What to check
stim_onset_idx - pre_stim_samples	Is this negative? If so, idx_pre gets clamped to 0 and samples_before_onset < pre_stim_samples — t=0 will shift right
idx_post - idx_pre	Should be pre_stim_samples + post_stim_samples. If shorter, the array was truncated
samples_before_onset	This directly controls where t=0 lands. Should equal pre_stim_samples (e.g. 600 at 30 kHz)
Recommended Fix to Investigate
Try temporarily removing extra_delay_samples entirely (set it to 0, making search_start = trigger_sample always). The search window then spans the full 120 ms of post-trigger data starting right at the boundary. This would confirm whether the skipping behavior is what's causing the misses. If alignment improves, the frame delivery delay is indeed overshooting the pulse position.

