Concrete Numbers at 5000 Hz
First, the key constants with real values:

ms_per_sample() = 1000/5000 = 0.2 ms per sample
bin_sample_count() = 50ms / 0.2ms = 250 samples (pre-stim window)
trial_recording_sample_count() = 100ms / 0.2ms = 500 samples (post-stim window)
Total trial_data / sync_data length = 750 samples
pre_stim_samples (Phase 2) = 20ms / 0.2ms = 100 samples
post_stim_samples (Phase 2) = 30ms / 0.2ms = 150 samples
120 ms search window = 600 samples
So trigger_sample = 250 always. The post-trigger data occupies indices 250–749.

The Core Bug: extra_delay_samples Is Overshooting
This is almost certainly your problem on both failed and misaligned trials. Here's exactly what's happening:


Frame delivery:
  trigger_wall_time_ms  ─── trigger fires (t = 0ms)
                                │
                                ├── Model 4100 fires pulse at ~1-3ms (hardware)
                                │   → pulse arrives at ADC sample ~5 to 15 (index 255–265)
                                │
  frame assembled ─────────────── at t = ~10-20ms (when Open Ephys finishes the frame)
  timestamp_emitted = t + 10ms
Then:


ms_delay = timestamp_emitted[0] - trigger_wall_time_ms  # e.g. 15ms
extra_delay_samples = 15ms * 5 samples/ms = 75 samples
search_start = 250 + 75 = 325
But the stim pulse is at index ~255–265. Search starts at 325, skips right past it. Onset not detected → fallback → t=0 placed at index 250 → window is wrong.

The reason: timestamp_emitted is the moment the frame finished assembling in the background thread. Each Open Ephys frame covers a chunk of time (e.g. 10ms of data at 5000 Hz = 50 samples per frame). The pulse is somewhere in the early samples of that first post-trigger frame, but timestamp_emitted reflects the end of that frame's assembly — making it appear the stim arrived much later than it did.

Breakpoints and What to Inspect
Breakpoint 1 — In RECORD state, on the self._frame_received_timestamps_ms.append(...) line:


data_frame.timestamp_emitted - self._trigger_wall_time_ms   → "frame delay" in ms
                                                              e.g. 15ms → 75 samples skipped
len(self._current_trial.sync_data) before concatenation      → how many samples so far
data_frame.sync_data_block.max()                             → does THIS frame contain the pulse?
If sync_data_block.max() >= 4.5V on the first post-trigger frame, the pulse is in samples 0–N of that frame, not at the end. But extra_delay_samples will skip 75 samples into it.

Breakpoint 2 — Right before the print(f"[DEBUG] onset search ...") in _update_trial_plot:


trigger_sample                           → always 250
extra_delay_samples                      → e.g. 75 (this is the likely culprit)
search_start                             → e.g. 325
search_end                               → min(250+600, 750) = 750
self._current_trial.sync_data[250:325].max()  → is the pulse HERE (in the skipped region)?
self._current_trial.sync_data[325:750].max()  → is the pulse here (in the searched region)?
If the first query returns >= 4.5V and the second doesn't — confirmed: extra_delay_samples is skipping the pulse.

Breakpoint 3 — After idx_pre / idx_post in Phase 2:


stim_onset_idx           → e.g. 250 (fallback) or 262 (detected)
idx_pre                  → max(0, stim_onset_idx - 100)
                           if stim_onset_idx = 250: idx_pre = 150 ✓
                           if stim_onset_idx = 255: idx_pre = 155 ✓
idx_post                 → min(750, stim_onset_idx + 150)
                           if stim_onset_idx = 250: idx_post = 400 ✓
samples_before_onset     → stim_onset_idx - idx_pre
                           should be 100 (= 20ms); if it's less, t=0 shifts rightward
Recommended Fix
Remove extra_delay_samples entirely. Set search_start = trigger_sample always:


# Remove this whole block:
extra_delay_samples: int = 0
if (self._trigger_wall_time_ms > 0 and len(self._frame_received_timestamps_ms) > 0):
    ms_delay: float = ...
    extra_delay_samples = ...

search_start: int = trigger_sample  # always start right at post-trigger boundary
The pre-trigger discard logic in process() already guarantees nothing before the trigger is in sync_data[250:]. Any crossing in indices 250–849 (120ms window) is legitimately post-trigger. The consecutive-sample check already rejects single-sample noise. The extra_delay_samples logic was meant to help but is actually making the window too narrow because it measures frame assembly delay, not stim hardware latency.

